{"key":"processedPost-20311975","value":{"id":20311975,"first":20291687,"last":20643574,"when":1406072574,"utime":"07/23/14 02:42 AM","content":"<blockquote>Quote:<br />Most people on here have usually insisted that contams in a properly-done bulk substrate grow DEFINITELY, NECESSARILY, GUARANTEEDLY, HAVE to be from contaminated spawn.<br /></blockquote><br /><br />Instead of capitalizing the adverbs it would have been more accurate to include the always-qualifying statement that if it contaminates PRIOR TO FIRST FLUSH it will be due to contaminated spawn.<br /><br />Mold is fast, but it won't land on grain spawn in a bulk substrate, germinate and then grow to sporulation before the live mycelium consumes it for lunch.&nbsp; When we spawn to bulk, the grains are fully recovered by live mycelium within 48 hours, usually less.&nbsp; The exception to this is when growers leave exposed grains on the surface.&nbsp; These can dry out, causing the mycelium to die back.&nbsp; Mold can then enter the grains and get a foothold.<br /><br />He could have mold mycelium embedded with the mushroom mycelium.&nbsp; I had a similar problem a few years ago with S75.&nbsp; Grow after grow would be fine until spawned to sawdust.&nbsp; Then, before first flush green mold would show its ugly face.&nbsp; I switched to a backup culture and the problem resolved.<br />RR","title":"Re: Cannot, for the life of me, figure out my contamination source.","forum":"Mushroom Cultivation"}}